INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'fcfc39dc-b387-4e7f-a253-1242237d658d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SolidJS Feature-Based Structure — Colocation Without the Barrel Export Tax$escape$,
  $escape$SolidJS's fine-grained reactivity model makes colocation especially powerful: signals, stores, and derived computations belong next to the components that own them. Unlike React, there's no reconciler overhead from re-exporting primitives through barrel files — but barrel exports still hurt tree-shaking in Vite/Rollup builds if you're not careful.

Organize by feature, not by type. A `features/editor/` folder should own `EditorStore.ts` (a `createStore` slice), `EditorToolbar.tsx`, `useEditorShortcuts.ts` (a custom primitive wrapping `createEffect`), and its own `index.ts` that exports only the public surface.

Avoid deep barrel chains. A root `src/index.ts` that re-exports every feature barrel forces the bundler to evaluate all modules eagerly. Instead, import directly from feature paths in routing: `import { EditorPage } from '~/features/editor'`. SolidJS's `lazy()` wraps these naturally — `const EditorPage = lazy(() => import('~/features/editor'))` — giving you code-split boundaries that align with your folder boundaries. Keep signals and stores private unless explicitly exported; this enforces encapsulation at the module level.$escape$,
  $escape$// features/editor/index.ts — controlled public surface
export { EditorPage } from './EditorPage';
export type { EditorState } from './EditorStore';
// EditorStore and useEditorShortcuts stay private

// app/routes.tsx
import { lazy } from 'solid-js';
import { Route } from '@solidjs/router';

const EditorPage = lazy(() =>
  import('~/features/editor').then(m => ({ default: m.EditorPage }))
);

export const routes = () => (
  <Route path="/editor" component={EditorPage} />
);$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
