INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6ca23b83-90c6-44a4-8705-1438807bd807',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SolidJS Component Design — Single Responsibility and the Primitive/View Split$escape$,
  $escape$SolidJS components run once — signals and memos handle updates, not re-renders. This makes the presentation/logic split even more natural: your JSX is static structure, your reactive primitives are the live layer.

Apply the 150-line rule by extracting logic into custom primitives. A primitive is just a function that returns signals, memos, or resources — no special hooks API needed. This keeps components thin and makes reactive logic independently testable.

The pattern: write a `createXxx` function that owns all reactive state, then pass its return value into a presentation component containing only JSX. The presentation component receives accessors (functions) as props — never destructure them directly or you sever reactivity. Use `splitProps` if forwarding a subset to avoid the same trap.

`createMemo` belongs in the logic layer, not inline in JSX. Derived values computed inline re-evaluate on every DOM expression pass; a memo caches and short-circuits updates. One responsibility per primitive: `createUserSearch` owns query state, `createUserPagination` owns page state — compose both at the container level, keeping each primitive and each view under 150 lines.$escape$,
  $escape$function createUserSearch() {
  const [query, setQuery] = createSignal("");
  const [results] = createResource(query, fetchUsers);
  const hasResults = createMemo(() => (results()?.length ?? 0) > 0);
  return { query, setQuery, results, hasResults };
}

function UserSearchView(props: ReturnType<typeof createUserSearch>) {
  return (
    <div>
      <input value={props.query()} onInput={(e) => props.setQuery(e.currentTarget.value)} />
      <Show when={props.hasResults()}>
        <For each={props.results()}>{(user) => <div>{user.name}</div>}</For>
      </Show>
    </div>
  );
}

export const UserSearch = () => <UserSearchView {...createUserSearch()} />;$escape$,
