INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8836c731-2f9c-45bc-8c80-fb9f41ba9d59',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SolidJS Internationalization — Signals, @solid-primitives/i18n, and the Intl API$escape$,
  $escape$Hardcoding strings in SolidJS components kills localization before it starts. Use `@solid-primitives/i18n` — it's built around signals, so locale switches trigger fine-grained reactive updates without re-rendering entire subtrees.

Define a `createI18nContext` with a dictionary object, then consume translations via the returned `t()` accessor inside your JSX. Because `t()` is reactive, only the text nodes that actually changed will update — no virtual DOM diffing needed.

For dates and numbers, skip moment.js entirely. The native `Intl.DateTimeFormat` and `Intl.NumberFormat` APIs are fast and tree-shake friendly. Wrap them in a `createMemo` keyed to your locale signal so formatting recomputes only when the locale changes, not on every render.

Never store formatted strings in `createSignal` and manually invalidate them — let `createMemo` track the locale dependency automatically. Use `createResource` if translations are loaded asynchronously from a CDN, pairing it with `<Suspense>` to stream locale bundles without blocking the initial paint.$escape$,
  $escape$import { createSignal, createMemo } from 'solid-js';
import { createI18nContext, useI18n } from '@solid-primitives/i18n';

const dict = {
  en: { greeting: 'Hello, {{name}}!', price: 'Price' },
  fr: { greeting: 'Bonjour, {{name}}!', price: 'Prix' },
};

const I18nContext = createI18nContext(dict, 'en');

function PriceDisplay(props: { amount: number }) {
  const [, { locale }] = useI18n();

  const formatted = createMemo(() =>
    new Intl.NumberFormat(locale(), { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD' }).format(props.amount)
  );

  return <span>{formatted()}</span>;
}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
